\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Fertility, Household Labour Supply and Agricultural Productivity: Instrumental
 Variable Evidence from Uganda
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Bjorn Van Campenhout
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the most basic level, subsistance farmers in rural Africa combine natural
 with human resources to make a living.
 They use mainly household labour on their own small plots to produce mainly
 for own production.
 As such, the quantity of family labour available is an important determinant
 of well-being.
 Family labour availability, generally believed to suffer much less from
 moral hazard problems, will be a direct function of the number of biological
 children within the household.
 For instance, more children means more hands to work on the field.
 At the same time, more children means mothers, and to a lesser extend siblings
 and fathers, will need to spend more time on reproductive chores.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Uganda has one of the highest fertility rates in the world and a substantial
 part of the population lives in rural areas making a living out of semi-subsist
ance agriculture.
 Even in the light of substantial reductions in child mortality rate, total
 fertility rates remain stubbornly high.
 On average, Ugandan women in rural areas bear 6.8 children 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "New9"

\end_inset

.
 The question on how familiy size affects well-being through its effect
 on production is therefore very important.
 For policy purposes, knowlege on how fertility affects time allocation
 to work on the field is important to guide efforts related to crop intensificat
ion and commercialisation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this study, we will investigate the effect of fertility on agricultural
 production at the household level.
 In particular, we will look at the effect of the number of biological children
 on household member labour input, as well as a range of productivity measures
 for different crops.
 Our identification strategy is a simple but powerful instrumetal variables
 approach inspired by the work of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "RePEc:aea:aecrev:v:88:y:1998:i:3:p:450-77"

\end_inset

.
 We use the fact that male ofsprings are prefered in conservative, patriarchal
 societies to construct a range of instruments.
 The exogenous variation in the sex of a child can then be used to determine
 the exogenous component of household size.
 Such a two stage least squares approach is expected to yield consistent
 estimates for the causal effect of fertility on agricultural labour supply
 and associated agricultural production within the household.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our findings suggest that high fertility rates cause women to work significnalty
 less on the family farm.
 Labour of men and children is unaffacted by family size.
 
\end_layout

