\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Hours worked 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section we will briefly look at some descriptive statistics on labour
 supply, one of the prime pathways through which fertility affects productivity
 and well-being.
 Most of Uganda has two cropping seasons.
 The first runs from January to June.
 The second cropping season is from July to December.
 The UNHS 2005/06 interviewed households twice over the course of one year
 to capture this feature.
 It visisted households in the begining of 2005 to caputure the second croping
 season in 2004 (that is, running from July to December 2004).
 Households were revisted at the end on 2005 to record information from
 the first croping season in 2005 (running from January to June 2005).
 In our study, we will only consider the 2004 cropping season.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Average-hours-worked"

\end_inset

 shows rime reported on the field along different dimensions
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The dimensions are mother, father or child; land preparation, input application,
 weeding and harvesting; and crop.
 The crops are the five most grown crops.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 One of the most obvious observations is that women do most of the work,
 and child labour is restricted to about one day per crop and activity during
 the entire season.
 This already indicates that the trade of between the time lost by the mother
 because of rearing the children and the time gained by extra hands is likely
 to work against agricultural production.
 Typical for Uganda is the low amount of time spent on applying inputs.
 Farmers in Uganda use very linited amounts of fertilizer and other inputs,
 so also the time spend on applying them is little.
 There is also some heterogeneity in the time spend on different crops.
 For instance, matooke requires less time than maize, both for men and for
 women.
 However, there are also difference between the sexes.
 For instance, women spend much more time cultivating sweet potatoes, and
 to a lesser extent beans, than men.
 
