\begin_layout Subsubsection*
The first stage regression
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first stage results that link sex of first child/children to fertility
 are reported in table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:firststage"

\end_inset

.
 The dependent variable is the number of children born, or what we will
 refer to as family or household size.
 Apart from the exogenous variable that is excluded from the regression
 elaborated in the next paragraphs, we include a series of control variables
 that are clearly exogenous to fertility in all 5 specifications of the
 first stage.
 The first, 
\emph on
agefirstborn
\emph default
, is the age of the first-born.
 We do this because our sample consists of households that are at various
 stages in the life-cycle.
 We expect that, the older the firstborn, the more children there will be
 on average in the family.
 The second exogenous control variable, 
\emph on
femhead,
\emph default
 is a an indicator variable that takes the value of 1 if the household head
 is female.
 The third, 
\emph on
urban
\emph default
, is an indicator function that takes the value of 1 if the household resides
 in an urban area
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In some specifications where we expect regional variation in the outcome
 variable to be important, such as for yields for certain crops, we also
 include dummies for the four regions in both the first and second stage
 equations.
 This addition did not significantly change other estimated paramers in
 the first stage.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Model (1) uses an indicator that takes the value of one if the firstborn
 in the household is a girl as an excluded instrument.
 The coefficient is significant at the one percent level and has the expected
 sign.
 Having a girl as a first-born increases family size on average by 0.126
 children.
 The controls are all significant and have the expected signs.
 If the firstborn is older, he or she is likely to have more siblings.
 Households where females are the head are smaller.
 This also holds for households that are residing in urban areas.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Model (2) uses as excluded instrument an indicator that equals one if the
 first two children born to the mother in the household are both girls.
 Using this instrument only makes sense if we confine ourselves to households
 that have at least two children, hence the significant reduction in the
 sample size.
 As in (1) the parameter is significantly positive according to expectations.
 Having a girl as a first-born and again a girl as a second-born increases
 family size on average by 0.122 children.
 The control variables are very close to the what they were in model (1).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Model (3) uses a contineous variable as excluded insturment.
 We calculated the share of girls among children as a percentage of the
 total number of children in the household.
 Again, the coefficient has the expected sign.
 A higher percentage of females within the households is associated with
 larger family size.
 This is consistent with 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Jayachandran01082011"

\end_inset

, who observe the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

try until you have a boy
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 fertility rule leads to an outcome where larger households have on average
 more girls.
 Again, the included instruments are similar to the previous models.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, model (4) uses mutiple excluded instruments.
 In specification (4), we use both the sex of the first-born and the percentage
 of girls in total number of children as instruments.
 The positive effects are also there in specification (4), but the results
 are not significant at conventional levels.
 As in all previous specifications, the exogenous control variables have
 the expected signs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While most of our instruments are significant and have the expected sign,
 they account for only a small part of the variance in the outcome.
 The high R-squared reported is mainly due to the explanatory power of the
 included instruments.
 If we regress the indicator variable of a first girl on household size,
 the R-square drops below 1 percent and the coefficient on the indicator
 is significant only at the 10 percent level.
 The F-value, another important indicater of the strenght of the instruments
 according to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "1995"

\end_inset

, also drops to 3.18.
 In other words, we have serious concerns that our instruments are weak.
 We therefore use inference that is robust to weak instruments.
 We rely on the Anderson-Rubin test statistic as implemented in the stata
 command weakiv.
\end_layout

